The Quay Concord is the coalition of Mafdet's senior ship captains who prioritized maritime operational reliability over inland politics.
It emerged during the Maritime Expansion period after the Strandline Compact freed Mafdet from inland court subordination.
The Concord's governing principle is harbor continuity: loading schedules, berth priority, and departure reliability are not negotiable for political reasons.
Senior captains in the Concord hold de facto authority over which ships access premium quay positions and loading windows.
The Concord maintains its own arbitration process for maritime disputes, parallel to but distinct from the Shrine of the First Claw's oath courts.
It views the Red Sand Accounts' aggressive debt-leverage tactics as threats to port stability and opposes cargo liens that disrupt quay scheduling.
The Concord considers the Shrine's oath-enforcement apparatus occasionally overcautious but respects it as a stability mechanism.
Its institutional concern is single: keep the harbor moving. Inland disputes are tolerated until they affect quay throughput.
The Concord holds no formal legislative authority within the Strandline Compact but can effectively veto cargo operations through quay access control.
Senior Concord captains are identified by the anchor-and-claw seal worn on the right clasp, denoting both maritime authority and Shrine recognition.
The Concord and the Harbor Wardens maintain separate authority chains that overlap at berth assignment.

